                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">excellent prints suffer from small size</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>4</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>0</span>
                      /
                      <span>0</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2005-03-25</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Anyone with a love of mountains or photography would be hard pressed to pass up Wolfe's "High Himalaya" offered at this price. Perhaps it would be difficult to fail to capture dazzling images, given the singularity of the books subject matter - the Himalaya are unique in their scope and majesty and even amateurs like me, equipped with a good camera, have returned from this awesome locale not only with the gnawing desire to return, but also with photos that blow friends away. Still, whenever I feel like I'd sacrifice my thumbs to be Himalaya-bound immediately, this book is one of the first I reach for. The clarity and diversity of presentation of the images makes me feel, alternately, as though I'm approaching a peak, at its base or viewing others from some overwhelming vantage point.
<br />
<br />On the technical side, a great thing about Wolfe's books is that he includes useful technical data on each photo - including camera, lenses, filters and film used for the shot, as well as exposure time - in well-designed appendices.
<br />
<br />Ultimately, however, the book's small size is its biggest drawback. Subjects of the monumentality of those in this book suffer from small-scale reproductions like these. The price, however, compensates well for this shortcoming.
<br />
<br />Finally, as to the comments of a reviewer below, baselessly disparaging Mr. Wolfe's work and drawing reckless conclusions about what this book implies for the state of our culture, I can say only that I consider his views reactionary. I own "Himalayan Odyssey" as well; though it is a remarkable book, especially given the technical limitations imposed by the equipment the photographer carried with him, those photos are not technically superior to Mr. Wolfe's in any way. Merely, the subject matter is vastly different; thus which book one prefers is a matter of taste, not "cultural" certainties. Honestly, my own photographs from this region attest that an amateur  would have a much easier time reproducing the work in "Himalayan Odyssey" than that in "High Himalaya."</span>
                  
